Mission Analysis (aka Business Analysis) is the first document Mission Analysis is used to define the mission need or the opportunity while characterizing the solution space and potential solution classes that could address a problem or take advantage of an opportunity. A mission describes what the system will do and the purpose of doing it. The mission statement describes Kipling’s “six honest serving-men” – who, what, when, where, why, and sometimes how (Kipling 1902). The mission provides the context for defining measures of effectiveness and for development of the Concept of Operations (ConOps) in the next phase if the mission solution is voted to move forward with development. The Mission Analysis Model provides the high level description for an application or feature. The purpose of generating the Mission Context Model early in the development process is to establish the basic needs, functions and behaviors so that systems and software level scope guardrails can be established. This mission analysis model pattern is constructed from a combination of the standard systems engineering pillars: the SEBoK, the INCOSE Handbook, and NASA's Systems Engineering Handbook. The mission analysis package contains:
  1. Problem Definition Canvas
  2. Pain Point Brainstorm & Analysis Canvas
  3. Mission Ideation
  4. Mission Context
  5. Stakeholder Analysis
  6. Mission Use Cases
  7. Functional Flow Block Diagram
[1] https://www.sebokwiki.org/wiki/Business_or_Mission_Analysis#Mission_Analysis_and_Concept_of_Operations

The Mission IPO Analysis is used to broadly define the scope that the mission will be impacting. An IPO (Input-Process-Output) Diagram is a very high-level diagram used for systems analysis that visually describes business processes with the description of each component in word. It shows a process key inputs and resulting outputs after a set of operations.

The Problem Definition Package is used to describe the problem that needs to be solved and help define the problem space. This model uses a canvas to diagram to guide the user to creating the Problem Statement. What Is a Problem Statement? A problem is a statement about an area of concern, a condition to be improved upon, a difficulty to be eliminated, or a troubling question that exists in theory or in practice that points to the need for meaningful understanding and deliberate investigation. For more details: https://www.isixsigma.com/new-to-six-sigma/getting-started/how-to-write-an-effective-problem-statement/ The results of filling out the Problem Definition Canvas is that the Problem Statement can be added in the Problem element notes shown at the top of the problem diagram. The Problem Statement is document in the folloing template: PROBLEM STATEMENT Brief description of the problem. Statements are clear, concise, and understandable without technical jargon. CONTEXT Context for the problem is provided to understand the various perspectives.

A stakeholder analysis helps you identify which stakeholders are being impacted by a change project, where each stands on receptiveness to the change, and which ones can impact a change project the most. Stakeholder assessment is a critical component of effective business change management because it increases the success of your stakeholder engagement and management. Read more at airiodion: https://www.airiodion.com/stakeholder-analysis/ The Stakeholders package contains the key stakeholder who have an interest in the system under design. This package contains a description of the key stakeholders including what they expect from the system and concerns from their perspective. An example of a good stakeholder template to document that stakeholders perspective is: ROLE The role that the stakeholder plays in the ecosystem where the mission will be executed. BACKGROUND Provide any background information on the stakeholder that helps to solidify their perspective to the development team. CONCERNS What are they concerned about from the mission. RESPONSIBILITIES What are their responsibilities in the mission context?

The Pain Point Analysis model is created to analyze a business process or product that is problematic and leading to stakeholder dissatisfaction. It may or may not be a real problem but is perceived as an obstacle that hinders the process customer or stakeholder from finding a solution. Pain Point Analysis is a useful tool when assessing the current state performance of a business process and seeking to identify areas to focus remediation activity based on the likely return on effort. Pain Point analysis should focus on the problem identification and extent of condition which can be input to the problem statement creation. When to Use Pain Point Analysis Pain Point Analysis is a useful tool when assessing the current state performance of a business process and seeking to identify areas to focus remediation activity based on the likely return on effort. In other words, where will improvement time and resources reduce the most process pain. Effective use of the method is reliant on having stakeholders with suitable knowledge of process' current performance as well as the availability of relevant process performance data (e.g. volumes, error rates} Why Use Pain Point Analysis Typically, processes will under perform across a range of areas - and a structured method for determining where to prioritize effort is critical to any process improvement exercise. Using Pain Point Analysis, a business analyst can guide an organization to agree on where maximum pain is being experienced and therefore where it is most essential to focus improvement effort and resources. Following Pain Point Analysis, Solution Ideation and Assessment are used to asses effort, feasibility and risk of solutions. Some Examples of Pain Areas that will be generated as part of a pain point analysis are:  
  1. Particular processes takes too long, which inhibits productivity. Current solutions waste too much time with minimal results.
  2. Spending too much money on their current solutions and they are either looking to save money, or get a better bang for their buck.
  3. Process where locating, procuring, and assembling all of the items needed takes longer than the value added part of the process.
For this model we defined a problem as a persistent or recurring event that frequently inconveniences or annoys process customers and/or stakeholders. The pain point analysis model pattern was created to provide several analysis diagrams that can be systematically used to identify and show the pain points, gaps, plusses, and deltas that stakeholders want to be fixed, from the perspective of each stakeholder. The model was generated through a series of workshops with multiple representatives for each stakeholder interactively providing input. The brainstorming workshops were systematically held with each workshop focusing on one of the model sections in the following order:  
  1. Completed the "Stakeholder Brainstorm"- who are the stakeholders of the process/product of interest.
  2. Completed the "Pain Point Brain Storm Canvas" for each stakeholder group by having a Pain Point Brainstorming workshop where the plusses, deltas, pain points, and gaps were generated.
  3. Completed the"Pain Point Analysis" with the stakeholder groups to rank and group pain points by occurrence and impact to the stakeholder
  4. Compile the results using the "Pain Point Analysis Report"

The Functional Flow Block Diagram package provides a general construct to systematically identify, describe and relate the functions performed by either the user or system to meet their goal.
A user FFBD helps with understanding what users are going to do. The System Functional Flow block diagram is a very useful tool in describing the top level functions that need to be performed by the system.
A functional flow block diagram is functionally oriented only and can be used as a starting point to map out order of operations or logic flow which can then be decomposed to define the system functional design and interfaces.

The model was generated through a series of workshops with multiple representatives for each stakeholder interactively providing input. The brainstorming workshops were systematically held with each workshop focusing on one of the model sections in the following order:  
  1. Completed the "Stakeholder Brainstorm"- who are the stakeholders of the process/product of interest.
  2. Completed the "Pain Point Brain Storm Canvas" for each stakeholder group by having a Pain Point Brainstorming workshop where the plusses, deltas, pain points, and gaps were generated.
  3. Completed the"Pain Point Analysis" with the stakeholder groups to rank and group pain points by occurrence and impact to the stakeholder
  4. Compile the results using the "Pain Point Analysis Report"

The Deltas Package contains negative elements of the process/product. These are different from pains in the sense that pains are smaller in scope and more fact based. The following template shows the best practice used for documenting this element when further clarification was need and what each section contains: Delta##- Name Deltas name should be action oriented and begin with a verb. DESCRIPTION Identify the opportunity for improvement by including things that can be changed so that the individual or team may be more effective in a concise manner. CONTEXT Some brief context should be provided that gives:
  1. Deltas should be specific in how/when they occur
  2. Deltas should be within the realm of possibility
  3. Deltas should be reviewed and acted upon

The Gap package contains the elements that contain the definition and description of individual gaps identified during the analysis. Specific details as to the nature of the gap and effects of the are summarized for each pain point. A gap is a specific problem that prospective stakeholder (or customers) of your system are experiencing. In other words, pain points are problems told from the prospective of you stakeholders themselves. The following template shows the best practice used for documenting this element when further clarification was need and what each section contains: Gap#- Name GAP DESCRIPTION Provide a brief description of the gap and what need is not being fulfilled. CONTEXT Provide a brief description of the context in which the gap is encountered or contributes to the overall problem IMPACT Describe the impact of the gap, such as the entire process breaks down, or the entire solution path is blocked.

The pain points package contains the description of individual pain points identified during the analysis. Specific details as to the nature of the pain point and effects are summarized for each pain point. A pain point is a specific problem that prospective stakeholder (or customers) of your system are experiencing. In other words, pain points are problems told from the prospective of you stakeholders themselves. The following template shows the best practice used for documenting this element when further clarification was need and what each section contains: Pain#- Name PAIN POINT DESCRIPTION Provide a brief description of the pain point and why it is a pain point vs a delta which is something that could be done better. CONTEXT Provide a brief description of the context in which the pain point is encountered or contributes to the overall problem IMPACT Describe the impact of the pain point, such as the entire process breaks down, or the entire solution path is blocked.

Pluses are the items that the individual or team wants to maintain and build upon. The Plusses package is different from the other packages in this model because it contains the positive elements associated with product or process. The Plusses package contains all of the plusses or things that the process/product is doing well. The following template shows the best practice used for documenting this element when further clarification was need and what each section contains: Plus#- Name DESCRIPTION Provide a brief description of the plus and why it is beneficial. CONTEXT Provide a brief description of the context in which the plus is encountered or contributes.

A user FFBD helps with understanding what users are going to do. The System Functional Flow block diagram is a very useful tool in describing the top level functions that need to be performed by the system.
A functional flow block diagram is functionally oriented only and can be used as a starting point to map out order of operations or logic flow which can then be decomposed to define the system functional design and interfaces.

A set of libraries and objects provided by this solution make short work of visualizing the stakeholder analysis of a project. Some things to consider when applying this pattern:

The Stakeholder Management Levels Diagram shows the ranking of the stakeholders and where their investment in the project needs to be to show that the project is successful. The mission context diagram helps to frame the Voice of the Customer (VoC) input into elements that can be traced and massaged into the first set of requirements in the ConOps process.

The Pain Point Brainstorm Canvas illustrates the different pains that the stakeholders are experiencing with respect to the problem and the problem statement. This diagram also shows the pluses or positive things that are being experienced now and the deltas or experiences that need to be eliminated or improved upon.
The pain point brainstorm canvas was created to captured the current lay of the land with regard to the business process/product being analyzed. A pain point brainstorm was created for each of the stakeholders from their perspective.
The pain point analysis also combine the common Plus - Delta analysis tool because the brainstorming workshops often generate discussion elements which identify what is going well and what needs to be changed. This tool asks participants to reflect on their continuous improvement and inform the changes needed to achieve higher performance. The Plus Delta inclusion involved drawing two additional areas in the analysis diagram, where one represents the positive feedback (what the group thinks went well) and the other represents the negative feedback (what the group thinks didn't go well and needs improvement).

Pain Point Analysis is a method for assessing the issues impacting the performance of a business process by considering the relative weighting of process issues across two dimensions. The analyst can choose the most relevant dimensions, however a typical combination is impact or severity combined with volume or frequency. An alternate to volume / frequency in some situations is detectability. The Pain Point Analysis diagram illustrates the impact that the different pains have on the process and that the stakeholders are experiencing with respect to the problem and the problem statement.
This diagram is to clearly reveal which pains needs to be addressed. Typically the Pain Points that are in the top right quadrants should be the highest priority to resolve.

The Pain Point Analysis diagram illustrates the impact that the different pains have on the process and that the stakeholders are experiencing with respect to the problem and the problem statement. </font> <font color="#ff0000"> </font><font color="#ff0000">This diagram is to clearly reveal which pains needs to be addressed. Typically the Pain Points that are in the top right quadrants should be the highest priority to resolve. </font>

The diagram from left to right represents the sequence of functions that a user/system performs to achieve their goal. Functionality of flow is enhanced using logic gates.
Each function block of the FFBD is decomposed to a lower level to derive performance requirements.
